📘 Holes in Graphs of Rational Functions
Definition:

A hole is a point on the graph where the function is undefined, but the discontinuity is removable. In other words, the graph “skips” that point instead of going to infinity.

Holes occur when a factor cancels from both numerator and denominator.

How to Find Holes

Factor the numerator and denominator completely.

Look for common factors that appear in both numerator and denominator.

Set the common factor equal to zero to find the x-coordinate of the hole.

Plug this x-value into the simplified function (after canceling the factor) to find the y-coordinate.

Example 1:
