📘 Domain Restrictions of Rational Functions
Definition:

The domain of a function is the set of all possible x-values for which the function is defined (does not break or become undefined).

For rational functions 
𝑓
(
𝑥
)
=
𝑃
(
𝑥
)
𝑄
(
𝑥
)
f(x)=
Q(x)
P(x)
	​

:

The function is undefined wherever the denominator 
𝑄
(
𝑥
)
=
0
Q(x)=0.

These points may result in vertical asymptotes or holes depending on whether the factor cancels.

Steps to Find Domain Restrictions

Factor the denominator completely.

Set denominator ≠ 0.

Solve for x-values that must be excluded from the domain.

Check for cancelled factors:

If a factor cancels with the numerator → hole.

If a factor remains → vertical asymptote.

