🟢 Trigonometry Applications: Waves, Circles, and Oscillations
1. Circular Motion

Position on a circle of radius 
𝑟
r (centered at origin):

𝑥
=
𝑟
cos
⁡
𝜃
,
𝑦
=
𝑟
sin
⁡
𝜃
x=rcosθ,y=rsinθ

𝜃
θ is the angle with the positive x-axis.

Angular velocity: 
𝜔
=
𝑑
𝜃
𝑑
𝑡
ω=
dt
dθ
	​


Example: A Ferris wheel, satellite orbiting a planet.

2. Simple Harmonic Motion (Oscillations)

Displacement of a mass-spring or pendulum system:

𝑥
(
𝑡
)
=
𝐴
cos
⁡
(
𝜔
𝑡
+
𝜙
)
or
𝑥
(
𝑡
)
=
𝐴
sin
⁡
(
𝜔
𝑡
+
𝜙
)
x(t)=Acos(ωt+ϕ)orx(t)=Asin(ωt+ϕ)

Where:

𝐴
A = amplitude (maximum displacement)

𝜔
=
2
𝜋
𝑓
ω=2πf = angular frequency

𝑓
f = frequency (cycles/sec)

𝜙
ϕ = phase shift

𝑡
t = time

